en little if any thought by most oi us. inong othe\nthe writer says\n\"We do not urge the humanitarian claims, the prob\npeal of this tragedy of innocent and helpless children. Ii\nI lie fate of any individual is a higher consideration. I n\noccidental civilization, of the progress oi i\nseriously involved.\n\"The wastage of the war has been a ser\nof which in the broad yet basic sense Amei\nwastage threatened, and, indeed, going on in\nmay very well carry Europe beyond hope of convalescence.\n\"The millions of children now starving for lack of food, i\nwhich we have a vast surplus, are the basis of the future. It the\ndie or grow up depleted in vitality the whole character of our civt\nfeation will be deteriorated. Europe's productivity will be reduce\n(Materially, and with the lowering of her production will come\nlowering of her standard of living. Our own trade will fall of)\nOur best market will be restricted. Debts owed us will not be pan\nIn short, our material prosperity will be seriously and perhaps pet\ninanentlv affected.\ntli-.t is ntilv one side of the nicture. In centra! Europe H\ntliete existed a body of scientific thought and its organized agencies\nof the highest usefulness to mankind in the conquest of knowledge.\nIt is one of the worst misfortunes produced by war psychology that\nthe importance of German science, that vast structure of method\nand knowledge created by German and Austrian genius, has ban\nforgotten because of the errors of a military caste or oi an erroneous\npolitical philosophy.\n\"Yet if this is destroyed, with the middle class now dying under\nour eyes, as it will be destroyed unless aid comes soon, we shall lose\none of the greatest resources of human enlightenment and progress\never developed by the genius of a race. European society will sink\nto a lower plane, will turn back upon its own path, and Ajnerica's\nloss will be heavy indeed.\n\"Finally we have to consider seriously our interest as a mem\nber of the white race in the preservation of its place in the world\nas against the possible encroachments of other races far outnum- Ye\nbering our own. This may seem a remote danger or fantastic. Lit'\nBut a glance backward in history will bring wiser second thought. U\nWe cannot afford to have a serious depletion of the numbers and j Ing\nvitalitv of the European people.\" jn\nBut after all it is the great humanitarian claim that appeals most jhtinfs\nstrongly to the average man. It is inconceivable that any real vario\nAmerican would be willing to see even one little one suffer the Lver\npangs of starvation, only to die, because of the sins or mistakes of the i\nthe fathers. Yet there are millions of children in Europe who won\nmust undergo all the agonies of the slow death by starvation unless i m\nBid comes to them from America. Millions get that -not hundreds the I\nor thousands, but millions oi little sufferers w hom only you can ulMf\nrelieve. Their own people are helpless to aid them. America is j i;is,,\nthe only place on earth today where there is a surplus of foodstuffs, dons\nand relief can only come to impoverished Europe from America. TJ\nThis appeal is made for the children, to save whom this great ef- L,\nfort is being made. No matter who is responsible tor the condition, case\nno matter how brutal and inhuman the German military machine '.'J\nwas, it is the children of Europe who must suffer and die unless\nthe great charity of the American people saves them.\nWhen you are asked to give, remember it is only to save a\nlittle child from untold aeony and death.\n\"s Vr\nA I\nHi\n1 V\nFsSsv\ni CI\nS T\nRUCKRIGEI I 1 EVATOR.\n$1 X12\n.tj.i\nI\n0. j\no\nDEL r'KATT\nvi IV 1 f Pratt. stafYankee ball\nMayer last season, Is between\nfwo Urea for the eomlnp; season.'\nHe has hla choice Of coaching the\nUniversity of Michigan team at\n6000 per season, or playing with\ntho Red Box for a salary said to\nhe much higher, fctt'a up to Del\nlUmsiiU.\nSCHOOLS OF WORLD\nINVITED TO REGATTA\n